Here's the standard approach:

### 1. Define each theme as a `ResourceDictionary`

```xml
<!-- Resources/Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Resources/Themes/DarkTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#1E1E1E</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#E0E0E0</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#4FC3F7</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Resources/Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#000000</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#FFFF00</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

### 2. Create a theme-switching service

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove existing theme dictionary (always the last one added)
        var existing = mergedDicts.FirstOrDefault(d => d.Source?.OriginalString.Contains("Theme") == true);
        if (existing is not null)
            mergedDicts.Remove(existing);

        var uri = theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark          => "Resources/Themes/DarkTheme.xaml",
            AppTheme.HighContrast  => "Resources/Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml",
            _                      => "Resources/Themes/LightTheme.xaml",
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(new ResourceDictionary
        {
            Source = new Uri(uri, UriKind.Relative)
        });

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("app_theme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static AppTheme GetSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("app_theme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        return Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var t) ? t : AppTheme.Light;
    }
}
```

### 3. Load the saved theme at startup

In `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(ThemeService.GetSavedTheme());
}
```

### 4. Reference theme keys with `DynamicResource`

This is critical — `StaticResource` won't update at runtime:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label Text="Hello" TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" />
    <Button BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource AccentColor}" Text="Go" />
</ContentPage>
```

### 5. Wire up the settings page

```xml
<!-- SettingsPage.xaml -->
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" Title="Theme"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
    <Picker.ItemsSource>
        <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
            <x:String>Light</x:String>
            <x:String>Dark</x:String>
            <x:String>HighContrast</x:String>
        </x:Array>
    </Picker.ItemsSource>
</Picker>
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object? sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (ThemePicker.SelectedIndex < 0) return;
    var theme = (AppTheme)ThemePicker.SelectedIndex;
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
}
```

### Key points

| Concern | Mechanism |
|---|---|
| Define colours/styles per theme | Separate `ResourceDictionary` XAML files |
| Swap at runtime | Replace the dictionary in `MergedDictionaries` |
| UI reacts instantly | Use `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) |
| Persist user choice | `Preferences.Set` / `Preferences.Get` |
